## DaisyUI 5 Breaking Changes (from v4) — Do NOT Use These

These v4 class names are **removed** in DaisyUI 5. Never use them:

| Removed (v4)           | Use Instead (v5)                                    |
|------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|
| `form-control`         | `fieldset` class on `<fieldset>` element            |
| `label-text`           | `label` class on `<label>` element                  |
| `label-text-alt`       | `label` class with normal Tailwind text utilities    |
| `input-bordered`       | Not needed — `input` has border by default           |
| `select-bordered`      | Not needed — `select` has border by default          |
| `textarea-bordered`    | Not needed — `textarea` has border by default        |
| `file-input-bordered`  | Not needed — `file-input` has border by default      |
| `card-bordered`        | `card-border`                                        |
| `card-compact`         | `card-sm`                                            |
| `tabs-bordered`        | `tabs-border`                                        |
| `tabs-lifted`          | `tabs-lift`                                          |
| `tabs-boxed`           | `tabs-box`                                           |
| `btn-group`            | `join` + `join-item` on children                     |
| `input-group`          | `join` + `join-item` on children                     |
| Table row `hover`      | `hover:bg-base-300` on `<tr>`                        |
| `btm-nav`              | `dock`                                               |

## Form Patterns (DaisyUI 5)

Use `<fieldset class="fieldset">` with `<legend>` for form groups. Use `<label class="label">` for individual field labels.

**Single field:**
```blade
<fieldset class="fieldset">
    <label class="label" for="name">Name</label>
    <input id="name" name="name" class="input w-full" placeholder="Enter name" />
    @error('name')
        <p class="text-error text-sm mt-1">{{ $message }}</p>
    @enderror
</fieldset>
```

**Select field:**
```blade
<fieldset class="fieldset">
    <label class="label" for="course">Course</label>
    <select id="course" name="course_id" class="select w-full">
        <option disabled selected>Pick a course</option>
        @foreach($courses as $course)
            <option value="{{ $course->id }}">{{ $course->name }}</option>
        @endforeach
    </select>
</fieldset>
```

**Grouped form:**
```blade
<fieldset class="fieldset">
    <legend class="fieldset-legend">Applicant Details</legend>
    <label class="label" for="first_name">First Name</label>
    <input id="first_name" name="first_name" class="input w-full" />
    <label class="label" for="last_name">Last Name</label>
    <input id="last_name" name="last_name" class="input w-full" />
</fieldset>
```

## Blade Component Architecture

Place reusable UI wrappers in `resources/views/components/`. Use Blade anonymous components with props and slots.

**Naming convention:** kebab-case, prefixed by domain when useful (e.g., `form-input.blade.php`, `data-table.blade.php`, `page-header.blade.php`).

**Example — form input component:**
```blade
{{-- resources/views/components/form-input.blade.php --}}
@props(['name', 'label', 'type' => 'text', 'required' => false, 'value' => ''])

<fieldset class="fieldset">
    <label class="label" for="{{ $name }}">
        {{ $label }}
        @if($required) <span class="text-error">*</span> @endif
    </label>
    <input
        type="{{ $type }}"
        id="{{ $name }}"
        name="{{ $name }}"
        value="{{ old($name, $value) }}"
        class="input w-full @error($name) input-error @enderror"
        {{ $required ? 'required' : '' }}
        {{ $attributes }}
    />
    @error($name)
        <p class="text-error text-sm mt-1">{{ $message }}</p>
    @enderror
</fieldset>
```
Usage: `<x-form-input name="email" label="Email" type="email" required />`

**Example — data table component:**
```blade
{{-- resources/views/components/data-table.blade.php --}}
@props(['headers'])

<div class="overflow-x-auto">
    <table class="table table-zebra">
        <thead>
            <tr>
                @foreach($headers as $header)
                    <th>{{ $header }}</th>
                @endforeach
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            {{ $slot }}
        </tbody>
    </table>
</div>
```
Usage:
```blade
<x-data-table :headers="['Name', 'Email', 'Role', 'Actions']">
    @foreach($users as $user)
        <tr class="hover:bg-base-300">
            <td>{{ $user->name }}</td>
            <td>{{ $user->email }}</td>
            <td><span class="badge badge-primary badge-sm">{{ $user->role }}</span></td>
            <td><a href="#" class="btn btn-ghost btn-xs">View</a></td>
        </tr>
    @endforeach
</x-data-table>
```

## Livewire + DaisyUI Integration

- Livewire components use the same DaisyUI classes in their Blade views.
- Use `wire:model` on DaisyUI form elements (`input`, `select`, `textarea`, `checkbox`, `toggle`).
- Use `wire:loading` with DaisyUI `loading` component for feedback: `<span wire:loading class="loading loading-spinner loading-sm"></span>`
- Alpine.js drives client-only interactions (modals, dropdowns, tabs) without server roundtrip.

**Modal pattern (Alpine.js + DaisyUI):**
```blade
<button class="btn btn-primary" onclick="document.getElementById('my-modal').showModal()">Open</button>
<dialog id="my-modal" class="modal">
    <div class="modal-box">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold">Title</h3>
        <p class="py-4">Content here</p>
        <div class="modal-action">
            <form method="dialog">
                <button class="btn">Close</button>
            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
    <form method="dialog" class="modal-backdrop"><button>close</button></form>
</dialog>
```

## Theming and Colors

- Use `data-theme` attribute on `<html>` for theme switching (already set to `"light"`).
- Use DaisyUI semantic color classes, not raw Tailwind colors for themeable UI:
  - `text-primary`, `bg-primary`, `border-primary`
  - `text-secondary`, `bg-secondary`
  - `text-accent`, `bg-accent`
  - `text-neutral`, `bg-neutral`
  - `text-base-content`, `bg-base-100`, `bg-base-200`, `bg-base-300`
  - `text-info`, `text-success`, `text-warning`, `text-error`
- Raw Tailwind colors (`text-slate-800`, `bg-white`) are acceptable for one-off elements that should not change with theme, but prefer DaisyUI semantic tokens for any themeable surface.

## Responsive Design

- DaisyUI components are responsive by default.
- Use Tailwind responsive prefixes to adjust component sizing: `btn-sm md:btn-md`, `card-sm lg:card`.
- Use `drawer` component for responsive sidebar navigation.
- Use `overflow-x-auto` on table wrappers for mobile.

## Accessibility

- Use semantic HTML: `<button>` for actions, `<a>` for navigation, `<fieldset>`/`<legend>` for form groups.
- DaisyUI components include sensible defaults; add `aria-label` when visual label is absent.
- Use `sr-only` class (Tailwind) for screen-reader-only text.
- Ensure color contrast meets WCAG AA — DaisyUI built-in themes comply by default.

## What NOT to Do

- **No hand-rolled buttons/inputs** — use DaisyUI `btn`, `input`, `select`.
- **No arbitrary color values** (`bg-[#1b1b18]`) — use DaisyUI semantic tokens (`bg-base-content`, `bg-primary`).
- **No `@apply`** — compose with utility classes directly in HTML.
- **No external CSS files** beyond `app.css`.
- **No v4 class names** — see the breaking changes table above.
- **No inline `<style>` blocks** in Blade templates.
- **No Bootstrap, Bulma, or other CSS frameworks** — DaisyUI + Tailwind only.
